Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” (Dickens, 220)

These novels often employ mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, although the specific purpose and nature of these moments differ. In "Oliver Twist," these experiences frequently offer glimpses into Oliver's inner world, revealing his pain and his understanding of the harsh realities surrounding him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, he relives the event vividly, as if in a dream, while desperately seeking help. The passage highlights Oliver's lack of control over the events that transpired, as well as the dire state of his health, as evidenced by his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms him, numbing his senses as he fails to notice the "unseen hand" carrying him away. He experiences his despair anew, detached from the initial shock of pain, replaced by a constant, gnawing fear. This raises the question of whose will is responsible for Oliver's misfortune, for it certainly wasn't his own. The shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little agency, unable to exert even a modicum of control over his fate, even when his life hangs in the balance. A sense of defeat also emerges, suggesting that Fagin has begun to break Oliver, forcing him to accept this despair and hindering his ability to react. Otherwise, it's reasonable to assume that Oliver would have made some effort, if only to save himself.

Another example of this dreamlike state is found in "Wuthering Heights": “The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours.”

A couple of years ago, I volunteered at an after-school program designed to assist elementary school students. While I tried to help all the children with their academic challenges, I excelled at tutoring in English and reading. One instructor asked me to work with a young boy named Adrian, who was in either third or fourth grade, as he was experiencing significant difficulties with reading. I quickly realized something wasn't quite right; his reading comprehension presented unusual obstacles. He would pronounce some letters flawlessly, while others were completely foreign to him – it was truly perplexing. I knew he was of Latino heritage, and while he spoke English fluently, his reading skills lagged behind. We struggled to make progress until the day Adrian's mother arrived. 

I was supervising a small group of children while the rest of the program participants were on a field trip when she walked in.  His mother only spoke Spanish, and my grasp of the language was limited, as I had only begun learning it. Nevertheless, we managed to communicate using a combination of broken Spanish and hand gestures.  That's when a crucial realization struck me: Adrian wasn't incapable of reading; he simply lacked a strong understanding of the English alphabet. Whether this insight ultimately helped him, I can't say for sure, but I sincerely hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the pervasive issue of language barriers in our schools, particularly in California. It also illustrates the importance of recognizing that challenges often aren't as apparent as they seem. Even for a child who speaks English fluently, reading can present formidable hurdles. I believe we can all agree that this issue exists, so the question becomes: what can we do about it? In Adrian's case, the solution was relatively straightforward: tutoring him in English reading, focusing on alphabet recognition and pronunciation. However, for children who have limited English proficiency, the solution is far more complex. There is no single, magic bullet. 

Dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, and ESL classes – none of these approaches, in isolation, can fully address this problem. The key lies in a multi-faceted approach that combines all of these strategies. 

[A dual language system, for instance, is a commendable concept.  It benefits not only children whose first language is Spanish, but all students. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically," according to research. Many fear that such programs are a wasteful use of resources and that the majority of students will not reap any benefits. This is a misconception.  If we implemented these programs more widely, rather than as an exception, all children would benefit.  

How do we achieve this? We don't need to require all teachers to be bilingual, which would be an unreasonable and impractical expectation. However, I believe there is no reason why we can't have bilingual aides or tutors to provide support.

From childhood, many of us are told about a force beyond our understanding, something vast and unknowable.  Some seek answers in organized religion, attending Sunday school or temple, while others find solace in introspection.  Tradition often guides our beliefs, leading us to embrace the faith of our upbringing. Yet, some reject these doctrines entirely, clinging to the certainty of their own limited perspective. Our values shift and evolve, reflecting a journey of self-discovery as we navigate the complexities of spirituality. We all yearn for a guiding light, a beacon in the darkness that illuminates our path.

"A cardinal," my father replied when I inquired about his favorite bird.  We sat on the porch, the rhythmic drumming of rain on the tin roof a constant backdrop to our conversation. The overflowing gutters cascaded water onto the wilting plants lining the edge of the porch.  He gazed out at the downpour, his eyes holding a mixture of contemplation and nostalgia.  He had become increasingly frail, his clothes hanging loosely on his frame. His hair, once thick and full, now seemed sparse and wispy. He avoided my gaze, lost in the relentless rain.  I felt a wave of loneliness wash over me, a fear so profound that I couldn't bring myself to voice my impending grief.  To speak of it would only make the reality more unbearable for both of us.  Instead, I embraced him, settled back into my chair, and moved closer, joining him in his silent contemplation of the fading light.

My father died in December, just five days after I turned twenty-two. The chemotherapy and radiation had prolonged his suffering, extending his life beyond the doctors' initial prognosis, but at what cost?  The purpose of his prolonged pain eluded me.  "What kind of God would allow this?" I whispered into the empty night, my prayers unanswered.  I had chosen not to witness his final moments, unable to bear the sight of life slipping away from the man who had brought me into this world. I wanted to remember him as he had lived, not as he died. I knew him better than anyone else, better even than his own family.  I was certain he wouldn't want me to be a passive observer at his death.  For three days, I retreated into my bedroom, curling up in a ball, waiting for the news.

No one contacted me.

The concept of the "Gothic Novel" presents an intriguing paradox, as aptly described by Ian Watt in his work "The Rise of the Gothic Novel." It oscillates between the familiar and the novel, a blend of "Old" and "New." This genre has faced a spectrum of critical responses, from derision and accusations of superficiality to fervent praise for its ability to evoke a sense of the "terrible sublime" (Burke). Horace Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto," considered the progenitor of the Gothic genre, masterfully merges elements of both ancient and modern romances, establishing a new mode of literary expression. Walpole ingeniously combines traditional theatrical elements with a contemporary emphasis on naturalistic descriptions, as he himself labels it "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). 

The Gothic literary tradition draws heavily on the aesthetics and conventions of medieval Gothic architecture, theater, and customs.  Even at the time of "The Castle of Otranto's" publication, the term "Gothic" had already been applied to a diverse range of cultures, styles, and eras. It often carried connotations of archaicism or cultural inferiority in comparison to the perceived advancements of the modern era. 

This juxtaposition of the theatrical "Gothic" with the novel's innovative format, which offered readers a more intimate glimpse into the characters' inner lives, contributes to the enduring appeal of the Gothic genre. It simultaneously feels both antiquated and refreshingly new to readers separated by time from its origins.

A prominent theme recurring in Gothic literature is the concept of chivalry.  Medieval notions of chivalry, the rigorous training of a knight, are both preserved and reinterpreted in Walpole's seminal work, "The Castle of Otranto." Chivalry holds particular significance for Gothic authors due to its embodiment of idealized qualities like bravery, honor, and competence. These authors, particularly Walpole, often lament the perceived decline of these ideals in contemporary society. Through the invocation of chivalric principles and conduct, the "Gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, foreshadowing the genre's evolution towards Romanticism. This romanticization serves as a vehicle to critique the present and aspire towards a more virtuous future.

Walpole, writing during a period of political turmoil and personal accusations, grappled with anxieties about the future. He may have, consciously or unconsciously, drawn a connection between the perceived moral integrity and inherent "goodness" of past eras and the perceived failings of modern society. This sentiment is evident in several characters, notably Frederic.  Before we even meet him, Frederic's character is imbued with chivalric attributes:

[Insert the passage describing Frederic here]

This description is replete with traditionally chivalric imagery. Frederic, a prince who has endured suffering and tragedy, is marked by the tropes of a "gallant and courteous Knight," albeit exaggerated, foreshadowing the Gothic tendency towards excess (66).

The intricate dance of moving goods from initial concept to satisfied customer is known as supply chain management. Coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver, this term encapsulates the delicate balancing act of planning, implementing, and controlling all stages – from raw materials to finished product delivery – to ensure customer needs are met with both speed and efficiency. 

At its core, a successful supply chain rests on six fundamental pillars: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information.  These elements, carefully orchestrated by skilled business managers, are the building blocks of superior customer service.

Production, the initial spark in this chain reaction, lays the groundwork for everything that follows. It dictates the "when," "why," "where," and "how" of creation, driven by a deep understanding of customer desires.  Market analysis becomes crucial here, acting as a compass guiding managers towards the products in highest demand.  Armed with this knowledge, they determine the precise quantities to be produced and the optimal location for manufacturing, factoring in both production volume and product quality to ensure customer satisfaction.

Once the production site is established, the focus shifts to meticulous scheduling and equipment maintenance. Every detail within production is a vital cog in the machine; neglecting any could result in costly delays and financial repercussions.  Consider, for example, the meticulous processes employed by retail giants like Walmart and Target. From employee uniforms to receiving shipments, every aspect of their operations is meticulously documented, ensuring smooth workflow and clear expectations.

The second pillar, "supply," encompasses the strategic choices made regarding a facility's core capabilities and its outsourcing partnerships.  A company might have multiple production divisions specializing in various aspects of a single product, each with unique equipment, personnel, and expertise.  Here, the manager acts as a conductor, strategically assigning tasks to the most suitable division or, in some cases, outsourcing certain processes to external companies. This strategic outsourcing aims to enhance "velocity" - the ability to deliver quality products with flexibility while simultaneously minimizing costs.

A street corner in a bustling city. A solitary figure stands, holding aloft a hand-made sign, its message stark and unsettling: "Hitler is alive in Burma." This is Ellen Page, famed for her role in the film "Juno," drawing attention to a distant and troubling reality. 

Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation currently under the control of a powerful military junta that seized power in 1962 through a violent coup. In 2007, a wave of protests swept through the country, marking the first public dissent in a decade. These demonstrations, led by Buddhist monks in their saffron robes, earned the name "The Saffron Revolution."  Initially met with a degree of tolerance by the government, the situation quickly escalated into a violent confrontation. Monks were met with force, their peaceful gatherings disrupted, and monasteries were attacked. 

Foreign journalists attempting to document the events were swiftly detained, with one, Japanese photojournalist Kenji Nagai, tragically losing his life on September 27th, 2007, simply for being present at a protest. While official figures claim a comparatively low death toll of 13, a defected colonel from the Burmese army, Hla Win, asserted that the true number was far higher, citing thousands of casualties. 

Sadly, this pattern of brutal suppression of dissent is not unique to Burma. Throughout history, governments have sought to maintain absolute control over their populations, often resorting to violence and intimidation. From the Roman emperors who claimed divine authority to the Japanese emperors revered as deities, and even contemporary leaders who wield power with an iron fist, the desire for absolute control remains a persistent threat to freedom.

The Tiananmen Square massacre of 1989 stands as a chilling reminder of this dark reality. Intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered in the heart of Beijing to express their dissatisfaction with the government's authoritarian rule. The official death toll remains shrouded in secrecy, with conflicting reports suggesting a significantly higher number of casualties. 

Another horrific example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militias, backed by the government, systematically slaughtered Tutsis and moderate political figures.  And of course, the atrocities committed by Hitler's Nazi regime during the Holocaust, where millions of Jews were murdered, serve as a stark reminder of the depths of human cruelty.

Duke Ellington's enduring impact on the realm of jazz is largely attributed to both his prolonged career and his exceptional aptitude for molding his musical ensemble. While his pianistic contributions may not be overtly prominent in the compositions selected for this analysis, Ellington's brilliance as a composer shone through in his ability to craft intricate and multifaceted musical pieces that allowed each band member to showcase their individual talents.  Ellington established a framework within which soloists could freely improvise, while simultaneously composing tightly arranged sections and melodic phrases that specifically catered to the unique styles of his musicians, thereby highlighting specific musical concepts. This approach also served to define the overall tone of the orchestra, resulting in cohesive and original sonic textures tailored to each composition.  Through his mastery of individual instrumental voices and their integration within the evolving ensemble, Ellington produced some of the most groundbreaking and exceptional works in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary, when discussing Ellington's distinctive sound and innovative spirit, cites "Creole Love Call" as a prime example of his lifelong practice of utilizing vocalization "as a jazz instrument." This early work exemplifies Ellington's talent for incorporating voice to enrich texture and color without relying on lyrical content. "Creole Love Call" also exemplifies Ellington's skill in complementing the styles of his soloists, a recurring theme throughout his career. This languid, measured twelve-bar blues piece unfolds across six distinct choruses:

Chorus 1: A call-and-response interplay between vocals and reeds, beginning with a smooth, melodic vocal line that gradually transitions to a more raspy sound towards its conclusion. 

Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo that expands upon the fundamental melody, emphasizing several extended blue notes.

Chorus 3: A soaring clarinet solo performed in a high register, accompanied by a subtle, syncopated piano passage.

Chorus 4: The full band replicates the first chorus, with a call-and-response pattern executed by the brass and reed sections.

Chorus 5: The pièce de résistance of the piece, as the reeds initiate the call-and-response in a high register, supported by syncopated stop-time rhythms from the brass and rhythm sections. 

Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, featuring a call-and-response exchange between vocals and reeds. In this iteration, the voice adopts the "growl" technique, functioning as an instrument during the solo.

Tag: A brief concluding section featuring a vocal flourish and a dissonant, novelistic ending provided by the trombone.

Ellington's artful utilization of voice to add another dimension of tonal color to this piece is but one example of a stylistic hallmark that permeates his entire body of work. 

In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington masterfully blends his talent for meticulous orchestration with his keen ear for tonal nuances. A call-and-response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing seamlessly merges the vocal qualities of Miley's playing with the instrumental facets of Cox's voice, generating a rich and complementary sonic tapestry. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" extends these ideas, as Ellington expertly employs Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a stalwart in Ellington's orchestra, to deliver the melody on muted trombone with exceptional effect.

A persistent void had always resided within her, an unyielding longing that refused to be satiated. This yearning first emerged during her adolescence, around the age of fourteen, and three years later, at seventeen, it remained an undeniable presence.  Over time, she realized her desire wasn't for material possessions but for companionship, a connection she hadn't found with anyone, not even the boys who occasionally expressed interest. They made their clumsy attempts at courtship, but she remained unmoved. This peculiar phenomenon puzzled her, prompting constant introspection and attempts to decipher its cause. Years of pondering yielded several theories, but none that felt convincing enough to warrant serious consideration. So, she navigated life, perpetually wrestling with the enigma of her desires.

Her daily life at home was typically tranquil. Her parents, both inherently calm and composed, rarely engaged in arguments, and disagreements with their daughter were equally infrequent. Their sole point of contention stemmed from her insistence on independence and expressive personality. Despite their serene nature, she countered their balanced energies with an exuberance and infectiously fun demeanor, making her a genuinely likable individual, a quality further enhanced by her inherent kindness.

However, today's atmosphere was anything but serene. As she wandered through the house, searching for inspiration, a sharp cry pierced the air, her mother's melodious voice laced with distress. She rushed to the kitchen, panic rising within her as she cried, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?"  She found her mother lying on the ground, writhing in apparent pain, uttering short, pained gasps. Her daughter immediately knelt beside her, reaching out to offer comfort. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to the... hospital," her mother gasped, her words fragmented and strained.  Her daughter understood the gravity of the situation. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where to pick you up."  Her mother weakly gestured, and in that moment, the daughter was acutely grateful for the physical training she had undertaken. She carefully lifted her mother, placing her gently in the car's backseat, and drove them to the hospital.

The hospital was a symphony of disinfectant and sickness, tinged with an underlying fear. However, her daughter was too consumed with her mother's well-being to notice. She rushed her mother inside and immediately summoned medical assistance. A cluster of concerned faces gathered around as someone swiftly procured a gurney and laid her mother upon it. They whisked her away for immediate attention, leaving her daughter to sit anxiously in the waiting area.

Her mother's injury stemmed from a fall from a stepladder while attempting to reach a vase from the top shelf of their highest cabinet.

This research aimed to investigate the link between adherence to a dietary pattern known as the "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) and the likelihood of developing chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke-related deaths.  A specific measurement, the "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," was used to gauge how closely individuals followed this dietary pattern. The aMed diet is a refined version of the Med diet, emphasizing plant-based foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, legumes, and fish, while limiting saturated fats and animal products. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous studies have shown a correlation between adhering to a Med diet and a reduced risk of both overall and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. Additionally, a clinical trial demonstrated that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in helping obese individuals lose weight and improve their cholesterol levels. However, these earlier studies did not specifically focus on stroke or stroke-related deaths.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, who had no prior history of CVD or diabetes. These women were participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a long-term study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over a 20-year period, from 1984 to 2004, researchers calculated an aMed diet score for each participant six times based on their responses to food frequency questionnaires ("FFQs") designed to assess their dietary intake over the preceding year.  More than 95% of the nurses remained in the study throughout this duration. The accuracy of the FFQs was confirmed through validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified by examining medical records, autopsy reports, or death certificates. In cases where records were unavailable, diagnoses were considered "probable" and included in the study, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts falling into this category. 

For each FFQ, factors such as body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated. Beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was also assessed. To account for individual variations and provide a more accurate representation of long-term dietary patterns, researchers calculated the average aMed score across two consecutive years. 

To minimize the influence of confounding factors (variables that could potentially distort the results), adjustments were made for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was employed to analyze the association between the aMed score and the risk of developing CHD and stroke. Separate models were used for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke occurrences.

The findings revealed that a higher aMed diet score, indicating greater adherence to the Mediterranean dietary pattern, was associated with a lower risk of developing both CHD and stroke in women.  Over the 20-year follow-up period, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combined fatal CHD and strokes) were identified. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The year 2007 marked a period of significant economic hardship in the United States.  Unemployment rates surged, the housing market experienced a dramatic downturn, and several prominent corporations faced severe financial distress. This economic downturn continues to have lingering effects, prompting an examination of its origins and potential solutions. At the heart of this crisis lies a complex interplay of factors, including risky lending practices and a vulnerable financial infrastructure. 

The government's encouragement of sub-prime lending, coupled with the pressure on entities like Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac to package these mortgages into complex financial instruments, played a crucial role. As borrowers defaulted on their loans, a ripple effect was triggered, destabilizing the financial system and spreading the crisis throughout the broader economy.

The seeds of this crisis were sown in the late 1990s, during the Clinton administration.  The administration's pursuit of economic growth and increased homeownership led to the relaxation of lending standards. This, unfortunately, created an environment ripe for the sub-prime mortgage crisis that unfolded years later.  Journalists, such as Steven Holmes of The New York Times, at the time raised concerns about the potential consequences of these relaxed regulations, predicting a possible financial crisis reminiscent of the savings and loan crisis in the 1980s.

The complex nature of mortgages in the years leading up to the crisis further exacerbated the situation.  Innovations like adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) interconnected various sectors of the economy with the housing market. This interconnectedness resulted in excessive reliance on the housing market, leaving both households and financial institutions vulnerable to price fluctuations.

The bursting of the housing bubble exposed the fragility of this system. Financial institutions that had invested heavily in mortgage-backed securities suffered significant losses. Major investment banks, including Bear Stearns, Lehman Brothers, and Merrill Lynch, faced substantial distress, leading to mergers, bankruptcies, and increased government intervention.

Exposition:  The Dreaded Battlefield of Storytelling

Exposition, that crucial juncture in a narrative, can be a double-edged sword.  On one hand, it's a chance to paint a vivid picture with your words, to captivate your readers with your mastery of language and your ability to transport them to another world. On the other hand, it can be the very thing that sends your audience reaching for the "Back" button, their eyes glazed over from an overload of information.  

The seasoned writer, Dr. Merlin, can attest to this struggle firsthand.  She's known to let out a frustrated cry when she encounters a deluge of exposition that drowns out the narrative flow.  The key, as any aspiring writer knows, is to "show, don't tell."  Yet, even the most experienced authors can fall into the trap of long, meandering passages that lack action or tension.

Exposition, in essence, involves directly informing the reader about events, often in a straightforward manner.  Think of it as a character in a film delivering a lengthy monologue, spewing out a torrent of backstory or crucial details, reminiscent of the "Ancient Mariner" reciting his tale.  In fiction, it's the author taking on the role of the omniscient narrator, delivering information rather than allowing the story to unfold organically.

Let's consider an example.  Imagine a story where a heroine's beloved is murdered.  Would you want the author to spend two pages simply stating facts about their relationship:  where and when they met, the extravagant wedding, the tragic demise?  Certainly not!

Instead, you'd expect the author to delve into the husband's character, revealing his love for his wife through his words and actions.  You'd want to see how his presence enriched the heroine's life, how it shaped her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams. A well-crafted introduction to the husband would allow you to connect with him emotionally, to feel the depth of his love and the weight of his loss.

The point is, exposition should be used sparingly and strategically.  Don't simply state the facts; bring them to life.  Instead of summarizing a character's history, weave it into the narrative, revealing their complexities through their interactions, their choices, and their inner thoughts.

Remember, as a writer, your goal is to engage your readers, to draw them into your world and make them care about what happens.  Don't let exposition become a barrier between you and your audience.

I watched two local news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio, on August 13, 2011.  The first was a live report from NBC 4. The lead story involved a stabbing incident in Ashley, Ohio. While the victim's name was withheld, the suspect, Shad Hostettler, was identified, and his mugshot was displayed.  The segment, lasting about two minutes, provided limited details, stating that the victim had been stabbed multiple times and Hostettler apprehended. The coverage seemed appropriately concise given the developing nature of the story. 

The next story focused on the shooting of 18-year-old Travis Buyers in the Sharon Woods area. Buyers was critically injured and no arrests had been made at the time. The SWAT team was investigating. This story felt somewhat abbreviated, and I wondered if this was due to the race of the victim and the neighborhood where the incident occurred.  A pattern I've observed is that media coverage of crimes involving minorities often receives less attention compared to similar incidents involving white victims.

The third story addressed a gunshot hole found in a MedFlight helicopter. Details about the suspected location and the determination that a .22 caliber rifle bullet caused the damage were provided. Crime-Stoppers offered a five-thousand-dollar reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest.

Next, the news briefly touched upon the anticipated rain and thunderstorms for the weekend, mentioning expected temperatures in the mid to low eighties. The segment felt intentionally short, likely intended as a "teaser" to encourage viewers to stay tuned.

A story about a robbery at a UDF on Clime Road was also covered. The suspect was described as a dark-skinned Black man wearing a hoodie, approximately six feet tall and weighing around one hundred and fifty pounds.  The emphasis on the suspect's race and skin tone seemed disproportionately long, which struck me as unusual.

Finally, the news reported on Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug trafficker. He had been sentenced to 300 months in prison for conspiring to distribute marijuana from Texas to Ohio.  The use of "300 months" instead of the more common "25 years" felt odd, perhaps an attempt to emphasize the severity of the sentence. The mention of Rodriguez's Hispanic background seemed tangential to the story.

The relationship between brothers is complex, characterized by a powerful and often unyielding connection.  This bond encompasses a spectrum of emotions, ranging from affection and admiration to envy and even cruelty. Brothers possess a unique understanding of each other, a level of insight that transcends typical relationships. They see their own reflection in their brother's eyes, not the image others perceive, but a truer, more authentic self.  It is in times of extreme adversity that the true nature of this bond reveals itself, whether for good or ill. The intensity of these emotions inevitably carries a weighty consequence.  Comprehending the emotions that stem from this fraternal tie involves confronting the repercussions they bring. 

The story "The Scarlet Ibis" delves into this theme, exploring the turbulent emotions inherent in a brotherly bond. Set against a backdrop of lush, vividly rendered scenery, two young brothers embark on a journey that ultimately proves futile. The story culminates in a scene where profound disappointment collides with intense pride, leaving only one brother to survive. The narrative weaves together the protagonist's direct experiences and interactions with his brother, providing a glimpse into the protagonist's complex emotional landscape and his perception of the world around him. These factors profoundly influence his actions.

The protagonist's actions are primarily driven by a powerful emotion: pride.  From their initial outings together to their final, fateful adventure, a sense of resentment festers within the protagonist towards his younger brother, Doodle. He yearns for a companion who can share in his outdoor pursuits, someone who can keep pace with him in physical challenges and adventures. This desire is unmet, as Doodle's physical limitations, stemming from a weak heart, make such activities impossible.  The protagonist's dreams of a brother who could join him in his explorations are shattered. This disappointment manifests as anger, even leading to a fleeting thought of harming Doodle. However, Doodle's innocent smile evokes a surge of affection in the protagonist, suggesting that his darker thoughts were ultimately fleeting. Deep down, a fundamental love for his brother persists.

The human brain is a complex system responsible for processing and generating creative outputs. As technology evolved, so too did the analogies used to describe its function. Initially, comparisons were drawn to rudimentary tools like wax tablets and papyrus scrolls, later evolving to encompass the book and, in modern times, the computer. However, it is crucial to remember that these metaphors, while helpful for conceptualization, possess inherent limitations and can lead to misconceptions.

Information processing begins with sensory input, where our organs translate physical stimuli – touch, temperature, sound waves, or light – into electrochemical signals. These signals undergo a series of transformations within the brain, guided by intricate algorithms operating in both bottom-up and top-down fashions. Consider, for example, the image of a black box against a white background. Bottom-up processing analyzes fundamental elements like color, orientation, and boundary delineations to identify the object as a box. Top-down processing, leveraging prior knowledge and context, refines this recognition, distinguishing it as a solid box rather than a mere void.

Once processed to a certain level, an attentional gatekeeper determines the significance of the incoming signal and directs it towards appropriate cognitive processes.  While your brain processes every blade of grass when you glance downward, a healthy attentional filter prevents conscious awareness of each individual blade. Conversely, your name, spoken amidst a cacophony, is readily singled out. This selective filtering occurs across multiple processing stages, constantly modulating the flow of information.

For effective processing, information must first be stored. The brain employs various memory systems, including sensory, working, and long-term memory. Encoding initiates this process, with different strategies employed for diverse sensory inputs. Verbal information, for instance, can be encoded structurally (based on visual appearance), phonemically (based on sound), or semantically (based on meaning). Once stored, information must be maintained. Studies on animals suggest that working memory, holding information for approximately 20 seconds, relies on a continuous electrical loop within a specific neuronal circuit. Long-term memory, on the other hand, is believed to be anchored in the structural organization of certain protein types.

Numerous models attempt to decipher the organization of knowledge within the brain, drawing inspiration from human memory retrieval patterns, computer science principles, and neurophysiological observations. The semantic network model posits that concepts are represented as interconnected nodes, with links signifying their relationships. For instance, in this model, "chair" would be linked to "table," which, in turn, might be linked to "wooden," and so forth.

In Aldous Huxley’s dystopian novel, *Brave New World*, a chilling critique emerges regarding the impending dangers of technological advancement and the capitalist system that perpetuates it.  The novel paints a picture of a society where communal harmony takes precedence over individual identity. From their earliest moments, citizens are meticulously conditioned to prioritize instant gratification above all else, becoming unwitting players in a larger societal game orchestrated by the omnipresent World Controller.

Through the lens of Marxist theory, particularly the concepts of homogenization and reification, Huxley’s anxieties surrounding the trajectory of these emerging systems become increasingly apparent. The novel's exploration of false consciousness, a key tenet of Marxist thought, is particularly striking. The general populace, preoccupied with personal gain, remains oblivious to the true power dynamics inherent in the economic structure. This ideological manipulation, akin to the control exerted over the proletariat in Marxist theory, is vividly depicted in the conditioning of *Brave New World’s* citizens.  The lower social castes, designated Delta, Gamma, and so on, lack independent agency; their desires are  shaped and amplified through hypnopædia, a technique that instills a fervent appetite for consumption and indulgence, ultimately serving the interests of the World Controller.  

The concept of hegemony, wherein a dominant group exerts control over subordinate groups, is also evident in this societal construct.  The lower classes remain unaware of the manipulative forces at play, effectively "embracing an ideology that upholds this system" - namely, capitalism and consumerism. The upper echelons, born with the capacity for awareness, choose to remain complicit, accepting their privileged positions.  Even characters like Bernard, an Alpha, barely challenge the status quo. The interactions between these social strata further underscore the perceived oppression inherent in this capitalist system.

Relationships in *Brave New World* are strikingly superficial, lacking the depth and complexity often found in human connections.  Huxley seems to suggest that the confluence of technological advancement and capitalism simultaneously erodes individual freedom and self-expression.  Love and intense emotions are absent; interactions are reduced to mere transactions, often characterized by superficial observations of physical attributes.  The unquestioning acceptance of their assigned positions within the social hierarchy by each class further exemplifies the socioeconomic impact of capitalism.  Their unwavering obedience reflects a Marxist perspective on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform to societal norms.

My time at University Park has spanned roughly two and a half years, encompassing four and a half semesters. Navigating the campus, a common challenge for many students, including myself, has often presented a hurdle. During my first year, I resided in an East Halls dormitory, situated at what felt like the easternmost edge of the campus, excluding the stadium and the Bryce Jordan Center.  Commuting from my home in Stuart Hall to classes held in distant locations, such as the Willard Building near the campus core, could easily consume up to 25 minutes on foot, particularly when adverse weather conditions prevailed, which is frequent in our State College climate. Through conversations with a recent alumnus, not much older than myself, I learned that the East Halls dormitories were once isolated from the rest of the university by vast expanses of unused land. This expanse has since been transformed into a tapestry of athletic fields, imposing new structures including the newly constructed Creamery and health services building, and a ring of apartment complexes. As our campus continues its expansion, traversing from one point to another becomes increasingly arduous. What, then, is the most effective solution to this mobility predicament? On a college campus, the bicycle emerges as a viable answer. However, the bicycle alone is insufficient. Students must embrace cycling, and the campus infrastructure must be designed with the needs of bicyclists in mind.

A recent conversation with a friend who recently rekindled his passion for cycling after a several-year hiatus prompted him to ponder why he ever abandoned it.  “Bicycles are exceptional,” he remarked, “while for a period, cycling wasn't perceived as fashionable, it's undeniably the most practical means of transportation.”  Beyond its physical benefits, cycling is the most efficient mode of travel.  A simple breakfast of oatmeal, accompanied by a moderate amount of exertion, can propel you over 30 miles.  Like many undergraduates, I now reside off-campus, located a comparable distance from the campus center as some dormitories.  The most astute decision I've made this year has been to acquire a bicycle.  Daily, I attend classes in Thomas Building, a location that typically requires a 25-minute walk from my residence. Cycling, however, can significantly reduce this duration to a mere 5 minutes, provided I maintain a brisk pace.  However, Pollock Road, the most direct route to Thomas Building from my home, is not always a smooth ride, whether on foot or bicycle.  Walking possesses its own merits, but personally, my schedule is too demanding to allow for extended walking periods.  Without my bicycle, walking would be my sole reliable option for reaching my classes.  Walking to Thomas daily would add an extra 30 to 40 minutes to my day, equating to over two and a half hours each week.  Adding to this the time required for walking to and from other classes, appointments, and other commitments, it becomes an unmanageable burden.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

Downwards I stared, mind blankly comprehending the view in front of me.  Unemotionally, silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding my mind analyzed the picture before my eyes.  Thoughts slipped into my mind and slipped out again almost faster than they appeared.  So smoothly and so cleanly my consciousness worked that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and liquid experience of what I was looking at. 
Once, on advice from an artist I worked with, I purchased an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain.   I had wanted to learn how to draw ever since I was six years old and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to processes the brain uses to interpret lines.  One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study.  Thus transforming an overwhelmingly detailed picture, for instance a bowl of fruit sitting on a table located in a kitchen that is connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture, that bowl of fruit sitting on a simple plane.   
At the time, staring down at the bowl in front of me I could not mentally project that artist’s frame.  I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonderment.  Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.  
Fingertips alighted on my chosen implement of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand passed through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life.  Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean.  Flakes of matter broke away from the whole and were carried away to nothingness.  Muscles tightening, jerking and spasming a little more quickly and anxious the second time, my hand smacked the handle of the toilet again.  The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.  
Mop gripped loosely in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the suckers who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid.  A few flushes more, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began mummifying itself until it resembled an oven mitt.   Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey….

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel.  Several factors come together to create this deadly vector of statistics for the youngest American drivers.  The National Institutes of Health explain that one facet of the problem is that the teen brain is literally not ready for the hazards of driving. Simple inexperience also lies at the heart of the problem. This inexperience not only causes more fatal accidents, but also a higher rate of vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road.  
Teens also fare far worse when they travel with their peers—which anyone with an iota of sense knows they do on a regular basis.  The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study that showed the following correlation: between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents occurring.
	California and other states have attempted to increase the safety of teen drivers by requiring temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours that teens may drive and prohibit other minors as passengers.
	But provisional driver’s licenses are, in my opinion, stopgap measures.  The real issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical markers, simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities.  Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license.  USA Today reports that Zuckerman has performed research suggesting a common desire among those under the age of 19-20 to take risks for the sheer thrill of the sensation.  It makes sense then, to delay driving at least until the tendency to thrill-seek has begun to level out.  If we continue to issue driver’s licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to see deadly accidents happening, but the death toll is likely to reach staggering proportions in the next few years.  By 2010, the Baby-Boomer’s babies will be eligible to drive and millions of new teen drivers will ready to hit the road.  
Legislation dealing with this issue would be reasonably straightforward.  Schools could continue to provide driver’s education classes to begin the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 could operate a motor vehicle.  A provisional permit could still be issued prior to granting a full driver’s license, and a certain number of practical driver’s training hours would still be required as well.  The specific number of hours required could be based on the number of hours already required by the majority of states (in California, for example, that number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult.)  Because the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform, national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—means of protecting teens across the nation. 
The legislation I suggest is by no means a novel idea.

In looking through the Library of Congress’s library of early Edison films, I decided to view all of the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions. My film study generally focused on describing the poetics for the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier characteristics present in a few of the later films. Largely, the trick film at the turn of the century is set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, features no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, there are some films at the beginning of the twentieth century that dare to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.
One of the most noticeable aspects that the trick films share in common is their filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, and drew its root from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One of the limitations inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side, and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they go out of the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.
Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of the trick films; most of them focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. Note, however, that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer’s eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single “shot” may actually be several joined together to produce the illusion of apparition or disappearing. Look carefully at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary’s severed “head” begins, even though the whole film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

‎	‏John Taylor of Caroline was an early and ardent proponent of Republicanism.  Though he was primarily an agriculturalist,‭ ‬that very profession along with his brief career in politics created a man known for his dedication and outspokenness in matters of personal freedom and government.  His dedication to an agrarian system was the basis for almost all of his opinions concerning the government.  It was his attempt to preserve and encourage what he considered the most superior of all careers that colored his arguments on sovereignty,‭ ‬Constitutionality,‭ ‬and even the judicial system.
‎	‏John Taylor believed that the United States had a great opportunity to create an ideal system,‭ ‬because there was no native tradition to hinder the creators of the government,‭ ‬which allowed for the establishment of a system of self-government.
