Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

My passion for social work stems from a deep desire to champion the well-being of children facing adversity, particularly those who have experienced abuse or neglect. I envision myself working within the Division of Family and Children Services, providing vital support to both vulnerable children and their families navigating challenging times.  The core values that I bring to this field – service, respect, ethical conduct, and a commitment to fostering healthy relationships – are not merely professional ideals; they are deeply ingrained principles that guide my personal life as well.

My journey towards social work began with a lifelong yearning to make a positive impact on the world.  During my high school and college years, I observed how some individuals struggled to cope with their problems, resorting to unhealthy or unproductive methods. Witnessing these struggles solidified my desire to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. While my initial goal was to understand human behavior, I wasn't certain about a specific career path. A pivotal experience occurred during a summer break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009.  A friend introduced me to a troubled teenager seeking refuge from an abusive home environment. This encounter sparked a profound realization within me.  Driven by a desire to help, I reached out to the boy's parents, offering my support and sharing my educational background. Although the situation highlighted the limitations of legal intervention, it ignited a passion within me to pursue a career where I could directly advocate for children in need.

Social justice is another fundamental value that resonates deeply with me.  As a society, we often celebrate individuality while simultaneously promoting conformity. This apparent contradiction raises questions about our true commitment to embracing uniqueness. I believe in challenging social norms and advocating for equality for all. Throughout my academic years, I actively participated in protests and demonstrations against injustice, expressing my individuality through my appearance, associations, and unwavering support for marginalized communities.  

My passion for social justice fuels my commitment to making a tangible difference in the world. [

This examination explores the biological and sociocultural perspectives on insomnia. The biological model concentrates on inherited genetic predispositions and medical health factors. Conversely, sociocultural models investigate the influence of environmental factors like race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status on sleep patterns. This analysis delves into these models, examining selected research to illuminate their intricacies and provide a comprehensive understanding.  Each study's findings are critically assessed, highlighting both strengths and limitations.

Sleep disorders can be classified into three primary categories: primary sleep disorders, sleep disorders linked to other mental health conditions, and sleep disorders arising from external factors. Primary sleep disorders encompass Dyssomnias and Parasomnias. Dyssomnias, characterized by difficulties initiating or maintaining sleep, include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS).  Parasomnias, on the other hand, involve abnormal behaviors or physiological events during sleep, such as Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders associated with mental health conditions are often linked to either Axis I (clinical disorders) or Axis II (personality disorders or mental retardation) diagnoses. This review primarily focuses on insomnia, with some exploration of broader primary sleep disorders, through the lens of biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes the role of genetics, inherited traits, and physiological factors in sleep regulation. Research has shown that neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin play a crucial role in controlling sleep-wake cycles. A study utilizing mice models revealed the presence of phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons, specifically involved in regulating sleep and wakefulness. Activation of these receptors promotes sleep, while inhibition can lead to reduced anxiety and sleep induction.  The administration of a GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep duration in the mice (Matsuki et al., 2009). These findings suggest that the mouse model can be extrapolated to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the GABAB receptor in humans. Dysfunction or absence of this receptor could potentially disrupt sleep patterns, requiring medication for adequate rest.  From a sociocultural perspective, if the phenotype is inherited, it could influence sleep regulation, and any alteration in the receptor could naturally disrupt an individual's sleep, potentially impacting various aspects of life, including academic performance, career success, and daily activities requiring focus and sustained attention.

This document explores three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD).  Firstly, it provides a concise definition of the disorder.  Next, the diagnostic process is outlined, highlighting common indicators or "red flags". Finally, the document concludes by offering strategies that teachers in inclusive classroom settings can implement to support students with CAPD. 

Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), describes the efficiency and effectiveness with which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information.  The American Speech-Language-Hearing Association (2005) defines CAPD as the perceptual processing of sound within the CNS and the underlying neurobiological activity that drives this processing, resulting in electrophysiological auditory potentials. Essentially, it's a condition where the brain struggles to properly process what is heard. Individuals with CAPD possess normal hearing acuity and are not classified as "hearing impaired."  The challenge lies in the brain's ability to translate sound, differentiating words and separating conversations from background noise.

The earliest mention of this disorder, then known as "auditory imperception," dates back to the mid-1950s (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Researchers were studying children with communication disorders. An Italian research team, composed of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari, began developing tests for these children in 1954. Building upon this work, Kimura introduced dichotic testing in 1961, formulating a model to explain the physiology of the CNS underlying dichotic perception (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference held in 1977 spurred further research on children with CAPD.

CAPD presents itself in various ways.  Individuals with CAPD may have difficulty localizing sounds, distinguishing between auditory events, recognizing sound patterns, or differentiating changes in speech, such as detecting sarcasm based on tone. They might experience auditory blocking, where one sound obscures the preceding one, and may struggle to synthesize auditory clues into meaningful information. Additionally, they may have difficulty determining the sequence of auditory information (Ferre).

Diagnosing CAPD involves a comprehensive evaluation that includes systematic observation of listening behavior and performance on auditory function tests.  Audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and other qualified professionals utilize a variety of measures to assess auditory-related skills (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This assessment may encompass questionnaires, surveys, and observations of auditory behaviors in response to specific stimuli.  Currently, there is no single, universally accepted test for diagnosing CAPD, and the underlying cause of the disorder remains unknown. Many tests present individuals with multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and require them to differentiate specific items, such as words or numbers.  More advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to these signals.

The play "Twelfth Night" explores the complexities of disguise, suggesting that while it can be effective for extended periods of deception, it ultimately carries a risk of losing one's true identity. Ending such a charade presents a significant challenge, as it may lead to social alienation.  Ultimately, individuals face a difficult choice: preserving their authentic selves or maintaining relationships with others who may be negatively impacted by the revelation.  

While some might react neutrally to uncovering a deception, others could experience offense or resentment. The play delves particularly into the complications of gender role reversal as a form of disguise, raising questions about the motivations behind such a choice. In Viola's case, her assumption of a male identity, "Cesario," is driven by a need for self-preservation in a foreign land. As she states, she seeks refuge with a "captain" who aided her in a past situation ("I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…" (5.1.247-249)). 

However, this strategy isolates her from female companionship, severing a crucial support network.  Furthermore, her convincing portrayal of masculinity leads to Olivia's infatuation, creating a complex web of mistaken identities. Olivia's declaration, "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay," (5.1.138) highlights the confusion and unintended consequences of Viola's disguise.  Additionally, Viola grapples with her own suppressed feelings for Orsino, who expresses his admiration for her: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1. 260-261).

While this might appear progressive, "Twelfth Night" can be interpreted as a reflection on how deception can expose hidden emotions, particularly in Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages suggest that these characters harbor unexpressed desires, brought to the surface by the presence of Viola/Cesario. For instance, is Olivia's attraction to Cesario rooted in his perceived masculinity, or does it reveal a deeper, unexamined inclination towards women?  One could argue that Olivia's swift shift of affection from Cesario to Sebastian, coupled with her eventual acceptance of Cesario/Viola as family ("A sister, you are she," (5.1.315)), suggests she is more likely satirizing the superficial judgments prevalent in her era.

German colonial rule is remembered for its harsh realities, particularly the atrocities committed against the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa.  However, such a vast empire cannot be reduced to a single narrative. The German colonial experience was as multifaceted as its geographical expanse, encompassing a range of policies and governing styles. Educational initiatives across the colonies mirrored this diversity. When the British assumed control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they encountered a significant population of educated and literate Africans, a testament to German educational efforts.  Contemporary accounts also lauded German educational endeavors in Kamerun and other colonies. 

South West Africa, however, presented a stark contrast. Unlike East Africa, where the colonial government established public schools and actively participated in the education of the indigenous population, the responsibility for native education in South West Africa was largely entrusted to missionary societies, albeit with limited government support. The German government, however, did invest considerable resources in the education of Europeans within the colony, establishing a system of state schools and providing substantial support and oversight for missionary institutions. These contrasting educational policies had enduring consequences for South West Africa, extending even beyond the period of German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, South West Africa remained largely untouched by formal education, with the vast majority of the population remaining uneducated and illiterate. A confluence of social, political, and economic factors contributed to this divergent experience. This paper aims to delve deeper into these factors, particularly by examining new research on the perspectives and attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards the indigenous African population.

A substantial body of literature explores education within the German colonial empire.  Most of these sources are in German and originate from the early twentieth century, spanning the period of and immediately following German colonial rule.  Early works primarily focused on describing the characteristics of educational systems in these colonies.  Subsequent English-language writings expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education across the various German colonies and more in-depth analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies highlighted significant variations in the educational systems implemented in different colonies.  The most prominent work directly addressing the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in both South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of these two colonies and investigates the factors contributing to the observed differences.  Cohen posits that the substantial settler population in South West Africa is a key factor explaining the distinctive features of the colony’s educational system.

Compared to other German colonies, South West Africa enjoyed a relatively temperate climate, though much of the territory is characterized by arid desert.  The European population of South West Africa reflected these relatively favorable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites resided in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in East Africa, the colony with the next largest settler population.

The evolution of popular music over the last century has resulted in a vast and constantly expanding array of genres. Pinpointing an exhaustive list proves challenging, as most, if not all, established genres like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, have spawned numerous subgenres and sub-subgenres. Among these, the subgenre of heavy metal rock has emerged as one of the most diverse and expressive forms of popular music in the past four decades.  

Its expressiveness stems from its ability to convey a wide spectrum of emotions, often leaning towards the more somber and intense ends. The genre's diversity is evident in its early iterations, where musicians quickly recognized its inherent flexibility and began to experiment, creating unique subgenres that in turn gave rise to even more specialized offshoots, a trend that continues to this day.


The heavy metal movement has reached a point where the sheer number of niche groups makes it difficult to define precisely what constitutes heavy metal. It has absorbed influences from various other genres, yet its origins remain significant. To truly appreciate the metal music prevalent today, one must first grasp the nature of the heavy metal movement itself, understanding why it transcends the confines of a simple genre categorization.

At its core, metal is a movement characterized by a distinct darkness. It can be described as a "music of more" – more bass, more volume, more intensity, and more theatrical elements.  It moves away from primitivism, emphasizing technical proficiency; metal musicians are renowned for their mastery of their instruments, a quality that shines through in their music.  Metal is also, perhaps unsurprisingly, a movement deeply intertwined with drug culture. The psychedelic drug boom of the mid-1970s fueled a sense of experimentation and pushed musicians to create unconventional and otherworldly sounds, often attributing their creations to the influence of these substances.  It possesses visceral and often dark qualities that were relatively novel to the music scene at the time, as much popular music lacked such a connection to the darker emotional spectrum.  Later generations of metal artists have also drawn inspiration from the dark, visceral elements that were prominent in the Romantic era. Lyrics such as those found in "Helter Skelter" by The Beatles exemplify this inherent darkness:

  

These lyrics, showcasing a darker side of The Beatles, evoke a sense of emotional turmoil and instability, possibly reflecting the influence of drug use. Considered by some to be one of the earliest examples of heavy metal, it was a direct response to a heavier, more intense Rolling Stones song. The Beatles aimed to demonstrate their own capacity for power and intensity, including this track on their iconic "White Album."

Long before the Surrealists painted their dreamlike canvases, Henri Rousseau, a Post-Impressionist artist, was meticulously crafting his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. His 1910 masterpiece, "The Dream," depicts not just a woman awestruck by the wonders of her dreamland, but also reflects Rousseau's personal aspirations as a painter. From the outset of his artistic journey, he yearned for recognition, acceptance, and acclaim from fellow artists and art enthusiasts. Yet, he grappled with a significant internal conflict in pursuing this ambition.  "The Dream" stands as the embodiment of Rousseau's lifelong struggle: to either conform to prevailing artistic styles to gain acceptance within the art world he deeply admired, or to forge his own unique path, embracing creative independence.

To truly understand "The Dream" through this lens, one must first delve into Rousseau's life story. Born in Laval, a town in northwest France, on May 21, 1844, Rousseau's father was a prosperous tinsmith and hardware dealer (Shattuck 47). Despite his upbringing, Rousseau received no formal artistic training. Instead, he worked for the French municipal toll service, earning him the nickname "gabelou," until the age of forty (Shattuck 46).  Tragedy struck when his first wife, Clémence, passed away, followed by the loss of eight infant children, leaving him with only his daughter, Julia, and profound grief (Shattuck 49).  Seeking solace and a new beginning, Rousseau turned to painting as a source of comfort and inspiration. Unlike his contemporaries who romanticized the peasant in their art, Rousseau, a true folk painter, captured the hopes and dreams of the everyday person.

Rousseau's yearning for acceptance within the art world is understandable when viewed in this context.  Not only was he self-taught and began his artistic journey later in life, but he also emerged during a time when many talented and established modern artists were gaining recognition. While he had been painting for years, Rousseau's work only began to receive widespread acclaim around the same time as Matisse's rise to prominence. According to Jan Gordon in "Modern French Painters," although they were artistic rivals,  Matisse and Rousseau differed not only in style and subject matter but also in their motivations for painting.  Gordon writes, "Matisse feared painting in a trite manner, while Rousseau aspired to paint in such a conventional style that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français" (92).

Throughout history, many brilliant minds have observed a profound connection between ethics and aesthetics, suggesting an underlying bond between truth and beauty.  I concur with this notion, believing there's a fundamental reason for this pairing.  John Keats, in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn," eloquently captures this sentiment: "Beauty is truth, truth beauty— That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." While we often acquire knowledge through formal education or personal experiences, our understanding of ethics and aesthetics seems to transcend these conventional methods.  Both fields, as Keats implies, resemble attempts at description rather than prescription. Our explorations into morality and beauty primarily aim to decipher the reasons behind a work's artistic merit or an action's ethical implications, rather than establishing rigid rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

Furthermore, any critique of art or morality ultimately falls short of fully grasping the essence of what constitutes goodness or beauty.  Consider the Mona Lisa, a masterpiece by da Vinci.  Discussions about its value might revolve around elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, yet these factors fail to fully elucidate its artistic excellence. When asked about a cherished work of art or literature, individuals often express a sense of ineffable quality,  preceded by phrases like, "There's just something about it," before elaborating further. I propose that both art and morality resist complete reduction to a mere description of their attributes. Flannery O'Connor aptly states, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate."  No matter how comprehensively we analyze the characteristics of a literary work, an intangible element remains, defying complete articulation.  I believe ethics shares this inherent quality.  As Wittgenstein observes, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental."  It is this elusive "something," this indefinable essence, which I posit as the most compelling aspect of both art and morality. This transcendental nature of both fields, I argue, forms a bridge connecting them.

The profound connection between morality and art stems from the fact that we experience both most powerfully on a  noumenal level,  a concept borrowed from Kant.  They resonate with us on a level that can be felt but not fully explained. This link intensifies when considering the art form of literature.  As McKean eloquently states, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Modern Germany stands as a powerful and unified nation, its cultural tapestry woven from the alpine heights of München to the Baltic shores of Kiel.  A singular spirit pervades from the banks of the Rhine in Köln, stretching through the heart of the country to the Elbe's embrace in Dresden. Given this unique cultural blend, it's no surprise that the Germany we know today has roots in a multitude of diverse sources and ancestral tribes.

Germania, the ancestral homeland of the Germanic peoples, holds a name shrouded in historical debate. Scholars and historians alike grapple with its origins. Tacitus, in his historical writings, attributed the name to the Tungrian tribe, suggesting they were previously known as "Germans" before crossing the Rhine and engaging in conflict with the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar, in his account of the Gallic Wars, first employed the term "Germanus" to differentiate between the conquered Gauls and the unconquered Germanic tribes who frequently crossed the Rhine, often under questionable motivations (Caesar, 50-40 BC).  He borrowed this word from the Gauls themselves, utilizing it as a marker of distinction. While the precise meaning remains elusive, some propose it originated from a Gaulish term for a neighboring people.  In the opening chapter of his first book on the Gallic Wars, Caesar writes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles” (Caesar, 50-40 BC).  Other theories posit that the name derives from the "ger," the spear used in Germanic warfare (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word "garim," meaning "to shout," suggesting a boisterous or vocal people (Names of Germany).

The Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," explored the origins of the Germans, stating, “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?" (Tacitus, 98) 

The Romans, for their part, held limited interest in Germania. While they ventured into Germanic territories for resources and occasionally launched military campaigns, they largely confined their presence to the periphery of this wild and untamed land. The Germanic tribes, meanwhile, flourished along the borders of the Roman Empire, trading goods acquired from their lands and contributing their skills as soldiers within the Roman legions (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17).

I lowered my gaze, my mind attempting to process the scene before me. It was a detached observation, devoid of strong emotion. I analyzed the picture with a practiced eye, yet it remained an abstract image, failing to spark any deep understanding. Thoughts flitted in and out of my consciousness, appearing and disappearing in rapid succession. My mind worked with such fluidity and precision that it felt as if I was merely experiencing the visuals, rather than forming my own thoughts about them.

Once, an artist I collaborated with suggested I read a book titled "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I'd always wanted to learn to draw, ever since I was a child, and this book promised to teach everything from the fundamentals of using a pencil to the intricate ways the brain interprets lines. One technique it emphasized was using a square frame to isolate a specific area within a complex image. Instead of being overwhelmed by intricate details, such as a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room, the artist could focus on the simpler essence—just the bowl of fruit on a plain surface.  

As I stood before the bowl, however, I couldn't mentally construct that frame. I was completely captivated, lost in awe. Picasso had his blue period, Monet adored greenery, and the Italian Renaissance masters embraced a vibrant palette. If I harbored any artistic aspirations, this scene felt like the beginning of my journey, the start of my own story—a work I envisioned as "Work in Brown."

My fingers brushed against my chosen instrument of creation, my muscles tensing and relaxing as my hand moved through space, transforming my mental intention into physical form. It felt like a potentially pivotal moment in my creative life. The water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Fragments of matter detached themselves, carried away into nothingness. My muscles tensed again, twitching and spasming with a growing sense of urgency. My hand slammed down on the toilet handle once more. The offending brown package stubbornly refused to budge, clinging to the bottom of the bowl like a tenacious slug.

Holding a mop loosely in my hand, my feet shoulder-width apart, a green tie feeling uncomfortably tight around my neck, I frowned slightly as I stared at the unpleasant collection of processed animal and plant matter that someone had left as a message for the unlucky bathroom cleaners at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more moments of quiet contemplation, and then my hand reached for the wall beside me. Grasping the end of the toilet paper, I began wrapping it around my hand, transforming it into something resembling an oven mitt. Standing straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a parent reaching into an oven for a Thanksgiving turkey…

The alarming rate of vehicular fatalities among teenagers highlights a critical issue demanding immediate attention.  Various factors converge to create this dangerous trend, with the National Institutes of Health identifying the immaturity of the adolescent brain as a significant contributing factor.   

In addition to developmental factors, inexperience plays a crucial role.  Studies, such as one conducted by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center, demonstrate a direct correlation between the age of passengers and the occurrence of traffic accidents, underscoring the heightened risk associated with teenage driving, particularly when accompanied by peers. 

Efforts to mitigate this issue, such as provisional licenses with restricted driving hours and passenger limitations, represent temporary solutions.  The underlying problem lies in the inherent challenges faced by young drivers in adequately managing the complexities and responsibilities inherent in operating a motor vehicle. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman, through his research cited in USA Today, suggests that even the age of 18 may be too young for full driving privileges, citing a prevalent inclination among individuals under 20 to engage in risky behavior for the sake of thrill-seeking.

Delaying driving until this propensity for risk-taking diminishes could prove beneficial.  Failing to address this issue will likely result in a catastrophic surge in fatalities as the next generation of drivers, the "echo boomers," reach driving age within the coming years.

A straightforward legislative approach could involve continuing driver's education programs while prohibiting individuals under 18 from operating motor vehicles.  A provisional permit system could remain in place, coupled with a mandated number of supervised driving hours, mirroring the requirements of many states, such as California's 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of supervised practice. Because the alarming statistics affecting teen drivers are prevalent across the nation, uniform national legislation would be a logical and potentially effective measure to safeguard young people nationwide. 

The proposed legislation is not unprecedented.

While exploring the Library of Congress’s historical film collection, I became fascinated by a group of early Edison films classified as “trick films.”  This collection, encompassing fifteen films from 1895 to 1901, primarily relied on innovative editing techniques to create illusions. My analysis focused on identifying the common stylistic elements found in the majority of these films, while also examining the unique characteristics that emerged in a few later examples.

A defining feature of the trick film at the turn of the century is its restricted setting. These films were typically confined within a frontal proscenium, meaning the camera maintained a fixed position and did not move to follow characters or objects. This composition, drawing inspiration from both theatre and vaudeville, often resulted in limited movement within the frame, with figures primarily moving side-to-side rather than towards or away from the camera.  A prime example is the film “Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel” (1900), where actors enter from one side and move back and forth along a horizontal axis, remaining within the confines of the proscenium even as they exit the frame.

The frontal proscenium style also dictated the camera’s framing, favoring long and occasionally medium shots. Close-up shots were entirely absent in these early trick films. This mirrored the theatrical tradition, where the audience would observe the entire performance within the established boundaries of the stage.  

Further reinforcing this theatrical influence, most early trick films adhered to a strict “one shot equals one film” approach. This convention limited the length of most films to approximately one minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also restricted the narrative possibilities, as most trick films focused on short, vaudeville-inspired tricks such as magic, disappearances, and substitutions, rather than developing complex storylines. However, it is important to note that the concept of a “shot” in these films might not always align with a single physical take. A single “shot” could potentially be composed of several individual takes spliced together to create the illusion of apparition or disappearance. For instance, a closer examination of “The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots” (1895), an early trick film, reveals the moment where the physical shot of Mary’s severed “head” begins, despite the film being presented as a single, continuous shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was a fervent advocate for the principles of Republicanism, emerging as a prominent figure in its early days. Though his background was primarily agricultural, his experience in this field and his brief foray into politics shaped him into a man known for his unwavering commitment to individual liberty and limited government. His dedication to agrarian ideals served as the foundation for his political beliefs, influencing his perspectives on sovereignty, the Constitution's interpretation, and even the judicial system.

Taylor envisioned the United States as possessing a unique opportunity to establish an ideal system of governance. He believed the absence of deeply rooted traditions allowed for the creation of a government truly reflective of the people's will. A strong believer in the inherent rights of individuals, he asserted that these rights were interconnected and mutually dependent. He argued that if one right were infringed upon, all would be weakened, diminishing their overall value. These fundamental rights, in his view, should exist beyond the reach of governmental control.  He contended that what some referred to as the "state of nature" favored those with physical strength and cunning, leading to an imbalance of power.  He believed that in a civilized society, this dynamic must be rectified.

To achieve this ideal society, Taylor proposed a government structure that acknowledged both the inherent goodness and potential for evil within human nature. He held firm to a dualistic view of morality, stating, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167).  He defined good principles as those safeguarding private property, promoting agricultural progress, and discouraging the excesses of capitalism. He believed that a government grounded in these principles would function equitably regardless of its administration, which he acknowledged would inevitably be influenced by self-interest.  He viewed self-interest as a fundamental human motivator, but deemed it detrimental when it superseded the common good and led to the creation of self-serving sub-societies that exploited others. A well-designed government, in his opinion, was essential to contain these inherent human flaws and prevent the erosion of ethical principles.

Like many of his Republican contemporaries, Taylor advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution, believing in a limited federal government with powers explicitly defined within its text. He recognized that an expansive federal government could become tyrannical and fiscally burdensome. However, he cautioned against a purely literal interpretation, arguing that without considering the intentions of the Founding Fathers, such an approach could lead to unforeseen and potentially harmful consequences. Furthermore, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the true foundation of the United States, emphasizing its portrayal of the nation as a union of sovereign states rather than a single, unified entity.

The data depicted in Figure 17 reveals a significant decrease in commuter log submissions during the project's third month, a trend that raised concerns.  Several factors could have contributed to this decline. The transition to winter in a New England setting likely impacted commuting patterns, particularly those relying on bicycles or walking. December, coinciding with the end of the fall semester, saw students and faculty consumed with academic demands and holiday preparations, potentially leading to a decline in log completion.  Additionally, the month-long winter break further minimized the need for campus presence, potentially causing log submissions to fall off.  The low number of logs in January, despite the resumption of classes, remains unexplained.

It is possible that the initial enthusiasm surrounding the project naturally waned over time, a common challenge for such initiatives.  To counteract this, a "Carpool Challenge Week" campaign was implemented in March, aiming to re-energize participation and successfully resulting in an increase in log submissions. This highlighted the importance of maintaining project momentum, navigating both general engagement fluctuations and the unique challenges posed by academic calendars and extended breaks.

A fundamental obstacle for any alternative commuting program is the deeply ingrained cultural preference for automobile independence.  To encourage participation, a variety of incentives, including gift certificates to local businesses and national chains, were offered.  Exploring the impact of larger prizes, such as bicycles, hybrid vehicles, or electric cars, could have further motivated engagement and potentially mitigated the project's observed dip in participation. While the existing prizes proved sufficient initially, increasing their value throughout the project, perhaps by adding bicycles in December and a hybrid or electric car in January, might have yielded greater results.

Exchange-traded funds (ETFs) are investment vehicles designed to mirror the performance of a specific index, commodity, or a collection of assets, similar to index funds. However, ETFs offer greater flexibility, trading like individual stocks on stock exchanges.  

ETFs provide the diversification advantages of index funds while also allowing investors the benefits typically associated with individual stocks, such as short selling, margin trading, and the ability to purchase fractions of a share.  

While these advantages are highly appealing, ETFs generally have lower expense ratios compared to traditional mutual funds.  However, it's important to note that trading ETFs incurs a commission, similar to buying or selling individual stocks.

Furthermore, the ETF market boasts a wide array of options, catering to diverse investment strategies.  Even with these clear benefits, it's prudent for discerning investors to critically assess whether the advertised advantages, like diversification, are truly realized and to what extent.

This analysis will focus on ETF IHF, comparing its performance to the top ten holdings that constitute a significant portion of its assets.  The goal is to determine if owning a single ETF like IHF provides comparable benefits to holding a diversified portfolio of its constituent stocks.  Additionally, we will explore whether alternative stock combinations within this group could potentially yield a more optimal return for a given level of risk (as measured by the Sharpe ratio).

Examining every holding within the ETF would be cumbersome, so we will concentrate on the top ten holdings, which collectively represent approximately 63.58% of the ETF's total assets. 

To gauge how well these ten stocks represent ETF IHF as a whole, we will leverage their current asset percentages, normalized to 100%, to estimate their contributions to a portfolio's beta and return.  This assumes the portfolio were composed entirely of these ten stocks in the same proportions as held by the ETF.  The calculated beta and return values are presented in the accompanying chart.

The chart reveals that a portfolio consisting solely of the top ten holdings generated a return 6.11% higher than the ETF, translating to a 16% increase in returns.  Furthermore, the beta of these top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than that of the ETF itself.  

Based on these preliminary findings, a portfolio comprising only the top ten holdings appears to offer both higher returns and lower risk (as indicated by the lower beta) compared to the ETF.  However, it's essential to consider whether these differences are statistically significant.  

To address this, we will determine the standard deviation of each of the top ten stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their cumulative standard deviation to that of ETF IHF.

Edgar Allan Poe considered "Dream-Land" to be among his superior poetic works. Within the poem, Poe employs the term "Thulé" on two occasions, a word traced back to the Roman poet Virgil by scholar Mabbott. Virgil utilized "Thulé" to denote an island situated north of Britain, perceived by the ancient Greeks as the outermost edge of their known world. While Virgil's usage is well-documented, another influential source should be acknowledged. Poe held a deep appreciation for German literature.

The inclusion of "Thulé" highlights Poe's familiarity with the works of Johann Wolfgang von Goethe.  Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," draws parallels between Poe's poem and Goethe's verse, suggesting that Poe drew inspiration from the German master.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned writer of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts—the first in 1808 and the second upon Goethe's death in 1832.  Within the second part of "Faust" lies a poignant short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This piece revolves around a king who, after his wife's death, descends into heavy drinking and mourning.  Overwhelmed by grief, he ultimately decides to end his life, bequeathing his possessions to his children except for a goblet, a memento of his deceased queen. He walks to a cliff, casts the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and takes his final breath. The character of the King of Thulé shares striking similarities with the speaker in Poe's "Dream-Land," possibly reflecting Poe's own experiences with loss and reliance on alcohol. 

 Notably, "Faust" was adapted into a romantic drama by H.P. Grattan in 1842, just prior to Poe's use of the term "Thulé" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe references "Thulé" twice in his collected works. While he employs the phrase "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," he utilizes "Thulé" twice in "Dream-Land," acting as bookends for the poem.  "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be viewed as companion pieces, with Poe's poem seeming to step directly into the emotional landscape of Goethe's work. The speaker in "Dream-Land" describes a desolate Thulé, plagued by darkness, loneliness, and the haunting presence of deceased friends, a world devoid of color. These elements resonate with the emotional turmoil of the King of Thulé, who, having lost his wife, grapples with profound loneliness and a loss of purpose.

Goethe's literary significance would have ensured Poe's familiarity with his work, particularly given Poe's admiration for Tennyson, who was influenced by Goethe. Moreover, numerous reproductions of Goethe's works circulated after their initial publication, further exposing Poe to his writings.

The question of whether a customer injured in a California grocery store from an applesauce spill could receive punitive damages hinges on the actions of the store manager.  

Legally, a plaintiff seeking punitive damages must demonstrate the defendant's conduct was not merely negligent, but rather exhibited a deliberate indifference to the potential harm their actions could cause. This means proving the defendant acted with malice, which in this context, could be characterized as intentional misconduct or, in the absence of intent, a reckless disregard for the safety of others. 

In this case, Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages might be successful. She could argue that the manager, Paul Martin, knew of the potential danger posed by the uncleaned spill, given prior incidents of similar accidents at the store. His alleged disregard for these past incidents and his prioritization of his dinner break over customer safety could be presented as evidence of a willful and conscious disregard for the well-being of shoppers. 

The strength of Palmer's claim rests on establishing the manager's actions as not just negligent, but demonstrably malicious. While the fact that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009 is compelling, proving the manager's state of mind and  conscious disregard for the risks will be crucial to securing punitive damages. 

The timeline of events is significant. On October 13, 2009, two employees, Rich Wayne and Mary J. Haddigan, alerted Martin about the applesauce spill. Martin, however, dismissed their concerns, stating he was on a dinner break and unable to address customer issues.  Tragically, an hour later, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. This incident occurred amidst a pattern of previous slip-and-fall incidents, further strengthening Palmer's argument that Martin was aware of the potential dangers and chose to ignore them.

Under California law, punitive damages are awarded in cases where a defendant's conduct meets a high threshold of culpability.  It is for the court to determine if Martin's actions rise to this level of malice, taking into account all the evidence presented.

My exploration of Islam began nearly four years ago during a course at CBC. One of the most compelling discussions we had centered around the perception of Islam – a question that feels even more crucial in today's world. Reflecting on the events since 9/11, I've witnessed a significant shift in media portrayals of Islam and its adherents in America, transitioning from a state of hostility to an almost overwhelming embrace.  It's hard to imagine, just over two decades ago, a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with his family's undeniable Muslim heritage, even being conceivable.

The Prophet Muhammad's biography captivated my attention. My prior understanding of his history painted a picture of a figure who forcefully converted individuals and subjugated tribes through military conquest. However, the biography presented a different narrative, portraying Muhammad as a misunderstood martyr, a figure who humbly engaged with others and invited them to embrace his teachings. This contrast intrigued me, as it challenged my preconceived notions.

Further comparisons between the ministries of Jesus and Muhammad's documented "miracles" also sparked my curiosity.  One striking example is the account of Muhammad multiplying mutton and milk to feed a multitude of people. This narrative style, emphasizing Muhammad's humility and reliance on divine guidance, led me to question whether it aimed to present him as a more relatable figure, somewhat akin to Jesus.

While I found this approach intriguing, it also raised concerns for me. The emphasis on Muhammad's supposed miracles, while well-intentioned, seemed to diminish the unique and unparalleled significance of Jesus Christ's life and miracles. It felt as if certain aspects of Jesus's story were being subtly appropriated.

The biography also presented numerous accounts of individuals converting to Islam independently, supposedly providing evidence of its truth. However, many of these accounts relied on hearsay, recounted through multiple intermediaries. This reliance on second-hand information, while intended to lend credibility, ultimately diminished the stories' impact and introduced a sense of uncertainty.

Perhaps my most significant discomfort stemmed from the biography's attempt to elevate Muhammad as a paragon of virtue – humble, wise, gentle, and endearing. This portrayal clashed with my understanding of historical accounts, which depicted a more complex figure. It left me wondering if modern Muslims are fully aware of the complexities surrounding Muhammad's rise to power.

The evolution of Christian thought after the life of Jesus presents a fascinating study. While the beliefs and teachings attributed to him formed the foundation,  the path Christianity took diverged significantly from its origins.  Contemporary society, marked by a heightened awareness of progress and change, is witnessing a shift in religious landscapes.  Traditional viewpoints, though persisting within certain segments of the population, might not hold sway over the broader trend. 

Looking towards the future, a growing awareness of Christianity's historical development is anticipated. This will likely fuel a desire to distinguish the doctrines that emerged over time from the core principles espoused by Jesus.  This process, though potentially spanning decades or even centuries, suggests an inevitable trajectory: a return to the essence of Jesus' message.

Imagine a movement gaining momentum, gradually peeling away layers of accumulated doctrines, much like a clock rewinding.  This could lead to a return to a purer form of Christianity, focused solely on the teachings attributed to Jesus himself.  As this trend takes hold in regions like the United States and Europe, it could reshape religious practices and beliefs,  bringing a renewed emphasis on the simplicity of Jesus' original message.

This shift, however, might not result in a decentralized or fragmented religious landscape.  Rather, the theological pendulum could swing towards greater uniformity.  Denominational and regional differences might gradually diminish, culminating in a more unified expression of Christian faith.  History offers numerous examples of such reversals, from the Roman Empire's transformation from persecutor to adopter of Christianity to the evolution of societal attitudes towards race and equality.

The success of this envisioned reversion hinges on a reinterpretation of Jesus' words, viewing them through a metaphorical lens rather than adhering to a strictly literal interpretation.  What, then, transpired between Jesus' lifetime and the present day?

Tracing the origins of Christianity, we encounter Judaism, from which it emerged.  By the time the Romans conquered Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., Judaism had already established itself as a monotheistic religion, with a divinely inspired scripture and a strong sense of religious authority.  While united in their core beliefs, the Jewish population was not monolithic, with various factions like the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and common people coexisting within its midst.

Upton Sinclair's "The Jungle" presents a stark and unsettling portrait of human nature, suggesting that at its core, humanity is driven by greed and self-interest. This inherent flaw is starkly illustrated through the actions of the factory owners and managers who prioritize their own success above all else. Their relentless pursuit of profit manifests in a callous disregard for the well-being of their employees and the environment. 

Sinclair vividly depicts the industrial landscape as a menacing force, "the line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This imagery emphasizes the environmental devastation wrought by the factories, a consequence that the owners seemingly ignore.  The disregard for human life is equally apparent in their treatment of their workforce. They exploit their employees, demanding excessive hours and offering little protection or support. This exploitation is further highlighted by the quote: "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar."

The absence of adequate labor laws during this period allowed the owners to operate with impunity, treating their workers as expendable pawns in their quest for wealth.  The workers, trapped in a vicious cycle of poverty and desperation, are left to fend for themselves amidst the harsh realities of Packingtown.  Their plight is further compounded by the failure of unions to offer meaningful assistance. In fact, Sinclair portrays these organizations as contributing to the problem, enriching themselves at the expense of the very people they supposedly represent.  The desperate circumstances faced by the working class are compared to slavery, highlighting the dehumanizing nature of their exploitation.  Sinclair states, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Authors often employ various literary devices to guide readers' emotions and perceptions of key themes. The effectiveness of these techniques can vary greatly. F. Scott Fitzgerald masterfully utilizes a range of such strategies in his novel, "The Great Gatsby." One notable approach involves pairing adjectives and nouns in unconventional ways to evoke a specific ambiance surrounding a subject. Fitzgerald also imbues symbols with meaning and subsequently leverages them to achieve a similar effect.  He skillfully employs this latter technique with numerous colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. Throughout "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald meticulously constructs meaning associated with these colors, particularly white/gray and red/pink, which he later utilizes to trigger specific emotional responses in readers concerning significant objects.

Fitzgerald associates white/gray with a sense of uniformity, with white connoting a certain elegance and refinement, while gray suggests a faded, antiquated quality. This association is established early in the novel through frequent depictions of these colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently described as being "in white" (8), a common attire for all characters—Nick wears "white flannels" (41) to Gatsby's party, Tom sports a "white shirt" (36) during his encounter with Myrtle, and Catherine appears "powdered milky white" (30). The sole exception to this monochromatic palette occurs when Nick observes Gatsby's party, where the "halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald further solidifies these color associations by applying them to commonplace objects and settings. As Nick commutes to work, he travels "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56). At Gatsby's gatherings, the names of guests appear as "gray names" (61) on Nick's schedule. Catherine's apartment is described as "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses"—a symbol of uniformity (28). Even ordinary individuals and places are rendered in shades of white or gray: Jordan and Daisy shared a "white girlhood" (19), the valley of ashes features "gray cars" and "gray land" (23), the "Italian child" by the railroad track is depicted as "gray" (26), and the dog-seller is characterized as "a gray old man" (27).

Having established a clear semantic framework for white/gray, Fitzgerald strategically employs these colors to signify insignificance or uniformity in relation to specific subjects. This technique is notably employed in his portrayal of Daisy. After an extended period devoid of significant use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster"; this visual cue subtly transforms Daisy's perception from a distinct character into a more uniform, almost generic entity, representing an object of Gatsby's desire and longing (74).  Fitzgerald further reinforces this impression of Daisy's homogeneity through additional instances of white and gray: "a gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18) and her "white" (115) dress preceding Tom and Gatsby's confrontation.

San Diego County's agricultural prowess stems from its pleasant, sun-drenched climate.  A variety of crops thrive here, including tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. The area boasts a strong demand for organic, community-supported agriculture products, with numerous local organizations facing extended waiting lists.  Organic eggs and milk are also highly sought after. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations, alongside opportunities for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational pursuits.  This type of agricultural model presents a unique opportunity for landowners to capitalize on government programs while simultaneously enhancing habitat, thereby fostering recreational use and creating avenues for farm tours and educational programs, potentially generating income or serving educational purposes.

Beyond tapping into a potentially profitable niche market, organic farming often leads to increased biodiversity in both plants and wildlife. This is due to the absence of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming practices can come with higher costs compared to conventional methods.  Intensive labor and management are required to control pests and weeds, and to fertilize the soil without chemical inputs. Consequently, losses are frequently greater in organic farming compared to conventional approaches.  Furthermore, smaller organic farms may lack the economies of scale enjoyed by larger operations.  Practices beneficial to wildlife, but unrelated to organic farming, can also add to labor costs. These include planting cover crops, implementing strategic grazing rotations, managing invasive species, and actively shaping plant growth to create specific conditions, such as edge habitat or patches of open ground.  These factors highlight the reasons why a landowner in this scenario might seek financial assistance or expertise in maximizing both profitability and habitat quality.

The chosen parcel of land is located adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It encompasses 160 acres of chaparral, non-native Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland, situated next to the Cleveland National Forest. This land falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, as defined by the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan.  Although the plan is currently under review, it already recognizes over a hundred plant and animal species that inhabit the area.  Many of these are endangered, including the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may face endangerment in the near future, such as burrowing owls.

This region has been inhabited by Native Americans for centuries before being settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This particular piece of land, part of an original homestead patent, likely served purposes such as grazing and/or wood production for many decades.  

The selection of this property was based on research conducted on a real estate website. I then explored available government programs to understand the realistic options a small farmer might consider for cost mitigation and wildlife conservation.  As a model of potential outcomes, I identified an organic farm in the same area.

The impact of cultural context on negotiation cannot be overstated.  Culture, a complex and multifaceted concept, is defined as much by its absences as its presences.  It resists simplistic categorization, defying neat labels and generalizations. Statements attributing uniform traits to entire nationalities, such as "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating," are inherently reductive and ultimately unhelpful. While recognizing broad cultural tendencies can be a starting point, a truly effective negotiator delves deeper, understanding the specific cultural nuances relevant to the negotiation at hand and how they might influence the dynamics at play.

Encountering a new culture inevitably involves personal reflection, as we naturally frame our experiences through the lens of our own cultural background. This can lead to comparisons, but it is crucial to avoid imposing our own cultural assumptions onto the situation.  

Comprehending a foreign culture or mindset requires a multifaceted approach, encompassing historical analysis, an awareness of its potential biases, and a willingness to approach it with open-mindedness.  Rather than seeking to judge or alter it, the key lies in acceptance and adaptation. Within the context of negotiation, particularly when facing a weaker bargaining position, respecting and working within the boundaries of another culture becomes paramount.  Navigating unfamiliar territory requires sensitivity to local traditions and beliefs, which can serve as bridges to overcome cultural barriers and facilitate progress.

It's important to recognize that cultural influences extend beyond national boundaries.  Within any given nation, companies often cultivate their own distinct corporate cultures.  These cultures manifest in various ways, from work hours and dress codes to communication styles, delegation practices, and even philanthropic initiatives. The diversity of American corporate culture, ranging from demanding work environments to more relaxed settings, even within regions and urban versus suburban contexts, highlights the richness and complexity of cultural expressions.  While some cultures may appear more homogenous on the surface, this can be misleading, often masking a deeper layer of internal diversity.

Values serve as the driving forces behind cultural behaviors, providing the "why" behind actions. Understanding these values is crucial in negotiation. For instance, a culture that prioritizes saving face or communal harmony might discourage public confrontations or criticism to avoid jeopardizing harmony. Conversely, a culture that values aggressive negotiation tactics might be less inclined to settle quickly.  

While acknowledging these broader cultural tendencies is essential, a successful negotiator also benefits from gaining insights into their counterpart's individual values and motivations on a personal level. This personalized understanding can significantly enhance the effectiveness of the negotiation process.

The statement "The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God,'" originates in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible. This very phrase serves as the starting point for St. Anselm's argument regarding the existence of a higher power. Notably, this belief also resonates with another prominent figure, Thomas Aquinas, whom we will be analyzing.  

Since both of these thinkers are defending the same concept – the existence of God, specifically the God depicted in the Bible – and our aim is to determine the strength of their respective arguments, we will, for the sake of clarity, assume they both hold this belief to be true.  Exploring alternative conceptions of God would hinder a direct comparison, as their arguments are fundamentally built upon this specific understanding.
